fuels, EVs, green energy.

01:50.280 --> 01:54.960
And I remember at the time you just went through, because you just went right through with how

01:54.960 --> 02:00.680
green energy isn't so green or clean, especially when we talk about electric vehicles.

02:00.680 --> 02:05.200
So before we even begin, before we even begin, I want to bring you back to the state of the

02:05.200 --> 02:07.440
union address.

02:07.440 --> 02:11.440
President Biden is giving the state of the union, it was February 7th, so not too long

02:11.440 --> 02:12.440
ago.

02:12.440 --> 02:14.360
And he goes totally off script.

02:14.360 --> 02:15.360
It's not on the transcript.

02:15.360 --> 02:16.360
It's not anywhere.

02:16.360 --> 02:20.320
He says, we are still going to need oil and gas for a while.

02:20.320 --> 02:24.640
And then he tells a little anecdote, an oil executive asked him why his company, why his

02:24.640 --> 02:29.040
company should invest in fossil fuel projects in light of the negative business atmosphere

02:29.040 --> 02:31.000
for oil and gas projects.

02:31.000 --> 02:36.480
And Biden responded, we're going to need oil for at least another decade and beyond.

02:36.480 --> 02:42.760
You coined this a while ago, the energy transition delusion.

02:42.760 --> 02:47.680
Tell me why.

02:47.680 --> 02:54.640
Well, in the world that I live in, and this is not universal, not universal, I like to

02:54.640 --> 02:56.120
believe words have meaning.

02:56.120 --> 03:02.820
So I sort of, let's start with, and I recognize that words are elastic and we change their

03:02.820 --> 03:04.320
meanings over time.

03:04.320 --> 03:06.160
But usually it takes a long time.

03:06.160 --> 03:11.400
So a transition means going from something from one place to another, it's a transition.

03:11.600 --> 03:14.160
There is no transition going on in the energy markets.

03:14.160 --> 03:16.120
It's just not visible in the data.

03:16.120 --> 03:19.680
So in my world also data matters.

03:19.680 --> 03:24.840
And the idea that we're in the middle of an accelerating transition is not showing up

03:24.840 --> 03:25.840
in the data.

03:25.840 --> 03:34.640
In fact, if we then go one step further and talk about aspirations, which is the aspiration,

03:34.640 --> 03:36.400
that's when you get to the delusion.

03:36.400 --> 03:41.840
It's not just that it's delusional to call this a transition because there isn't one.

03:41.840 --> 03:47.200
And to restate what I mean by that is we're 20 years into what we could call the era of

03:47.200 --> 03:49.920
climate awareness, at least 20 years into it.

03:49.920 --> 03:55.160
The Western world was spent directly about $5 trillion, and I believe probably indirectly

03:55.160 --> 03:56.160
another $5 trillion.

03:56.160 --> 04:01.360
Well, let's say rounded up to about $10 trillion to avoid using hydrocarbons over the last

04:01.360 --> 04:02.880
20 years.

04:02.880 --> 04:06.760
And the share of the world's energy coming from hydrocarbons has indeed gone down in

04:06.760 --> 04:07.760
those 20 years.

04:07.760 --> 04:12.520
It's gone down from 86% to 84%.

04:12.520 --> 04:17.120
So that doesn't look like a rapid transition after $20 trillion of spending.

04:17.120 --> 04:18.520
It doesn't look like a transition.

04:18.520 --> 04:24.040
In fact, it's not a transition because over that same time period, the quantity of hydrocarbons

04:24.040 --> 04:29.000
consumed in absolute terms has gone up, and to put it in sort of relative terms has gone

04:29.000 --> 04:35.760
up by a quantity equal to adding 5 or 6 Saudi Arabia's worth of oil production in terms

04:35.760 --> 04:36.880
of energy equivalent.

04:36.880 --> 04:40.720
So that's the world's using more of everything, so that's not a transition.

04:40.720 --> 04:44.960
That's a feel like, you know, the better word to be transformation, we're adding new

04:44.960 --> 04:50.240
form of energy to the broad energy mix, which is a lot of windmills and solar arrays.

04:50.240 --> 04:51.240
This is true.

04:51.240 --> 04:54.720
We're adding new kinds of machines like electric vehicles.

04:54.720 --> 04:58.720
This is also indisputably true, and then we're going to add lots more of them.

04:58.760 --> 05:00.400
But that's not a transition.

05:00.400 --> 05:05.960
In fact, all of history, the development of new ways of producing and delivering energy

05:05.960 --> 05:07.440
to society have been additive.

05:07.440 --> 05:13.160
In fact, there's a sort of last point that I made many times I should make again.

05:13.160 --> 05:15.760
It's not that I like windmills.

05:15.760 --> 05:18.440
I've been in wind farms that stress the horizon in China.

05:18.440 --> 05:19.440
I think they're oppressive.

05:19.440 --> 05:21.360
I like solar arrays.

05:21.360 --> 05:23.160
In a way, my first patent was a solar device.

05:23.160 --> 05:28.120
It actually was a photo detector for guiding missiles, but I was a cold warrior back in

05:28.120 --> 05:30.440
the day, so I like the technology.

05:30.440 --> 05:32.200
I think I understand the technology.

05:32.200 --> 05:33.600
I'm a fan of the technology.

05:33.600 --> 05:37.160
If I were making a prediction today, I would say that the share of the world's energy coming

05:37.160 --> 05:42.840
from wind and solar in the coming decade will at least double, at least setting aside all

05:42.840 --> 05:45.520
the money being thrown at it foolishly.

05:45.520 --> 05:49.760
Even without that, we're going to increase the use of it because it's more cost effective

05:49.760 --> 05:50.760
than it ever was.

05:50.760 --> 05:53.200
So it has an enormous role, really important.

05:53.200 --> 05:58.240
But here we are today, to make the point again, all this excitement about wind and solar.

05:58.240 --> 06:05.320
As of right now, after trillions of spending, wind and solar combined provide the world

06:05.320 --> 06:10.560
one third as much energy as burning wood globally, burning wood.

06:10.560 --> 06:12.440
Wood is the oldest energy source known to man.

06:12.440 --> 06:16.880
We still get triple the energy globally from burning wood than we do from wind and solar

06:16.880 --> 06:17.960
combined.

06:17.960 --> 06:20.040
That's not because wind and solar won't take over wood.

06:20.040 --> 06:21.920
It has an America finally.

06:21.920 --> 06:26.840
So we now get twice to three times more energy from wind and solar than we do from burning

06:26.840 --> 06:27.840
wood.

06:27.840 --> 06:28.840
But it just takes time.

06:28.840 --> 06:29.880
It costs a lot of money.

06:29.880 --> 06:36.720
So the point of the delusion language is not meant to be an invective, although I guess

06:36.720 --> 06:39.160
it's obviously provocative.

06:39.160 --> 06:43.760
It's not there in the data where we are.

06:43.760 --> 06:47.000
And the more difficult thing to answer is, well, why can't we get there?

06:47.000 --> 06:48.400
I mean, so we heard it from the president.

06:48.400 --> 06:54.000
In a, I guess you could call it a form of social Tourette's, maybe.

06:54.000 --> 07:00.240
I mean, I'm not sure why Trump had social Tourette's even more epically than this president.

07:00.240 --> 07:02.480
Any president goes off script.

07:02.480 --> 07:05.480
So he says something that he has to know is true.

07:05.480 --> 07:10.280
And his energy secretary has since he said that off script remark, been running around

07:10.280 --> 07:15.040
the country, repeating that statement, actually went to the biggest energy conference in the

07:15.040 --> 07:21.720
world is zero week that my friends, Dan Jurgen, you know, pioneered and created down in Houston.

07:21.720 --> 07:25.400
And it brings people from all over the world and all forms of energy, not just oil and

07:25.400 --> 07:26.400
gas.

07:26.400 --> 07:30.680
She went there, secretary of energy, said, again, we're going to need oil and gas for

07:30.680 --> 07:32.260
a long time yet.

07:32.260 --> 07:37.960
And she sort of modified that, not just 10 years, when the reason she modified it with

07:37.960 --> 07:42.760
sort of more open ended, how long we'll need it is obvious.

07:42.760 --> 07:46.880
If you thought, if you thought as a business, pretend it's your money, that you have to

07:46.880 --> 07:50.520
make multi-billion dollar investments today and the government is going to ban your product

07:50.520 --> 07:52.720
in 10 years.

07:52.720 --> 07:53.720
Would you make those investments?

07:53.720 --> 07:54.720
Well, of course not.

07:54.720 --> 08:00.480
And of course, the current level of investing oil and gas is at a epic, if cyclical low,

08:00.480 --> 08:05.560
maybe lower than in relative terms than it's ever been in modern modern history.

08:05.560 --> 08:08.920
And why, why, why are the investments down?

08:08.920 --> 08:12.600
Is it because the oil and gas industry is afraid of competition?

08:12.600 --> 08:14.880
I don't think they're afraid of competition.

08:14.880 --> 08:18.160
What they're afraid of is regulation and taxation.

08:18.160 --> 08:22.560
And so you slow down and wait to see when things calm down and being simplistic, there

08:22.560 --> 08:23.560
are lots of factors.

08:23.560 --> 08:28.040
But if you're on a board and you're sort of thinking about these things, you know, you're

08:28.040 --> 08:32.680
making a lot of money now at current prices, even if even the current soften prices.

08:32.680 --> 08:33.680
What's the hurry?

08:33.680 --> 08:38.360
Let's just wait and see how things settle out and see what, if they're serious, I mean,

08:38.560 --> 08:39.760
I guess I would.

08:39.760 --> 08:43.800
This, by the way, this, this is already the same phenomenon as already in playing out

08:43.800 --> 08:50.840
in utility scale wind and solar where investments are down as subsidies get complicated.

08:50.840 --> 08:57.040
Nobody knows what the rules are as in as real costs have risen both for the costs of the

08:57.040 --> 09:05.000
machines and as the financing costs have risen because of interest rates and as uncertainties

09:05.000 --> 09:10.280
have risen with respect to if you're the developer going to put billions to work, you

09:10.280 --> 09:14.600
might, you might begin to worry about the tolerance of markets to high cost energy.

09:14.920 --> 09:21.440
And one of the things that is sort of central to the trope of the energy transition is that

09:21.440 --> 09:22.600
wind and solar are cheaper.

09:22.760 --> 09:24.240
That's just central to the thesis.

09:24.440 --> 09:26.120
It's baked into every forecast.

09:26.680 --> 09:33.560
And yet there is no jurisdiction in the world, in Europe or United States, no state and no

09:33.560 --> 09:39.240
country in which the increased penetration of wind and solar has led to reduced utility

09:39.640 --> 09:42.400
grid costs have all been associated with higher costs.

09:42.840 --> 09:49.800
So if they're cheaper and we're at epic levels of spending, I'm waiting for the cheaper power

09:49.800 --> 09:52.520
if you're a consumer and the inverses happen.

09:52.520 --> 09:58.720
So I think, you know, cooler minds setting aside the hyperbole around all this stuff and

09:58.720 --> 10:03.240
the anxiety about why we have to do this, which is beyond obvious what the motivations are.

10:04.440 --> 10:13.480
You know, the combination of scale imposing real costs, the combination of the exposure of

10:14.200 --> 10:19.400
the fragility of energy systems that the Ukraine invasion illustrated, because what Europe did

10:19.400 --> 10:23.000
was build a more economically and structurally fragile energy system.

10:23.480 --> 10:28.600
And by that I mean both by depending on an unreliable source of cheap energy, but also

10:29.320 --> 10:34.120
failing to build in their own borders, reliable sources of cheap energy.

10:34.600 --> 10:35.320
Right.

10:35.320 --> 10:40.280
So all of this, let me, you packed up, you threw out a lot of great information there.

10:40.280 --> 10:46.920
I just want to go back to one thing, that the Biden administration was talking about being,

10:47.640 --> 10:52.600
going to zero missions, totally green energy out at 2035 or 2050.

10:52.600 --> 10:54.520
All those dates really have been thrown out the window.

10:54.520 --> 10:56.920
They were just dates probably just to get out there, right?

10:57.480 --> 11:00.600
The numbers and the facts and the data didn't support any of that, right?

11:01.560 --> 11:06.520
No, there's no, there's, I think what we have is the Energy Information Administration,

11:06.520 --> 11:11.640
which is the Department of Energy's, I mean, tautological information agency.

11:12.360 --> 11:14.200
It's pretty, it's pretty apolitical.

11:14.200 --> 11:18.360
They've been very good over the, over the decades in providing data based on what's

11:18.360 --> 11:21.480
actually happening as opposed to policy aspirations.

11:21.480 --> 11:26.280
Their goal is not to make the policy, but to make forecasts, report data.

11:27.480 --> 11:30.600
Make forecasts based on stated policy.

11:30.600 --> 11:36.600
And they just issued their latest analysis and they show that pushing out to 2030, 2035, 2040,

11:36.600 --> 11:38.520
we don't get anywhere near zero missions.

11:38.520 --> 11:40.920
If you implement everything in the Inflation Reduction Act,

11:41.560 --> 11:46.200
set aside the Orwellian name for that, but all the spending, which is hundreds of billions,

11:46.200 --> 11:50.600
literally probably direct spending and mandated spending.

11:50.600 --> 11:53.640
Cause a lot of these things have mandates that are off book spending.

11:53.640 --> 11:59.160
So there's probably a trillion dollars of spending in the two pieces of legislation,

11:59.160 --> 12:05.240
Infrastructure Act, Inflation Reduction Act on wind solar transmission and electric cars.

12:05.240 --> 12:10.760
And what you get is, you know, something like 15 to 20% reduction in US CO2 emissions by

12:11.320 --> 12:16.840
2040 or so, which, okay, I mean, that's not zero, but it's not zero missions.

12:16.840 --> 12:21.560
And more importantly, as the EIA points out, and now there's this, that reduction,

12:21.560 --> 12:24.680
which is about a gigatonic carbon dioxide, by the way,

12:25.240 --> 12:29.400
we've already gone down about a gigatonic carbon dioxide in the last 20 years,

12:29.400 --> 12:32.680
mostly because of the cheap shale gas replacing coal, of course.

12:32.680 --> 12:37.960
But that's wiped out by three to four years of increased coal consumption

12:38.600 --> 12:41.880
in China alone, never mind India, Indonesia and other places.

12:41.880 --> 12:43.880
So there's, there's sort of this bizarre,

12:46.440 --> 12:51.160
it's almost surreal ignoring of what's going, really going on in the world.

12:51.720 --> 12:57.640
Which is CO2 emissions are going up as countries expand and chase energy that's cheap.

12:57.640 --> 13:03.720
And the CO2 emissions reductions coming in the United States come at staggering costs

13:03.720 --> 13:06.040
and have no effect on the overall global trends.

13:06.680 --> 13:16.440
And even Bill Gates at the last great gathering that gets vilified in Davos,

13:16.440 --> 13:19.800
gave a, you know, private interview and talked about all this stuff.

13:19.800 --> 13:23.640
And he, and he said, and I don't think I'm gonna get the quote wrong.

13:23.640 --> 13:24.920
So two things that are important.

13:25.560 --> 13:31.000
One is that even if we get to zero emissions by 2050, he doesn't think we can.

13:31.960 --> 13:35.000
Things we have to try, obviously he said that a lot, but we're not going to.

13:35.000 --> 13:40.840
But even if we got there, then that would not mean that the world's warming won't continue.

13:40.840 --> 13:46.680
The models would show the world will continue to warm roughly as much as the models purport

13:46.680 --> 13:47.400
it will do now.

13:48.600 --> 13:50.120
Whether you believe the models or not, it's not the point.

13:50.120 --> 13:54.760
The models don't show any material change going out for the next century after that,

13:55.640 --> 13:57.480
even if we spend that kind of money.

13:57.480 --> 14:01.080
The thing that really bothers me, what animates most of my work is not,

14:01.720 --> 14:07.400
it's not just that it's a delusionary to think that we can get rid of hydrocarbons quickly.

14:08.440 --> 14:08.920
Not never.

14:08.920 --> 14:13.000
Never is different than quickly, but quickly meaning in the foreseeable future in decades

14:13.720 --> 14:17.880
is that the cost of doing this is economically and socially destructive.

14:17.880 --> 14:21.480
It is, in my view, immoral.

14:21.480 --> 14:23.320
And it's immoral for this reason.

14:23.880 --> 14:32.040
The whole world has, really all of history, pursued the goal of increasing wealth

14:32.040 --> 14:34.520
for the maximum number of people, increasing productivity.

14:34.520 --> 14:39.640
Productivity is always defined very simplistically, but 100% accurately,

14:39.640 --> 14:43.880
getting more outputs for fewer inputs of dollars, labor and materials.

14:44.440 --> 14:49.080
The energy transition aspirations get the same outputs, if you're lucky,

14:49.080 --> 14:52.200
with increased inputs of dollars, labor and materials.

14:52.840 --> 14:57.320
This is, it puts more simply, this is wealth destroying.

14:57.880 --> 15:01.320
And at the scales we're talking about, I don't mean having a few percent of electricity

15:01.320 --> 15:05.720
from wind and solar and 100 million electric cars, that's irrelevant.

15:05.720 --> 15:07.160
It's in the noise, frankly.

15:08.040 --> 15:10.840
But the scales imagined, it's profoundly wealth destroying.

15:11.400 --> 15:15.160
And the people who are impacted by that are not the wealthy.

15:15.800 --> 15:17.320
So the wealthy are less wealthy.

15:17.880 --> 15:19.240
Okay, no one cares.

15:19.960 --> 15:24.360
It's the wealth destruction of the middle class and the people who are poor.

15:26.360 --> 15:32.840
It's indescribably offensive to me to have a path that's doing that,

15:32.840 --> 15:37.160
which is not the same as saying, because it always gets, one label is all,

15:37.160 --> 15:39.880
then you don't care about what we have to try to do.

15:41.160 --> 15:42.680
I care about changing energy systems.

15:42.680 --> 15:43.560
I may not agree with you.

15:44.600 --> 15:46.760
It was like, it's like an interrupter.

15:46.760 --> 15:51.240
I haven't met anyone who would say they're pro-pollution.

15:51.240 --> 15:52.840
They want more pollution in the future.

15:52.840 --> 15:54.120
We're all on the same side.

15:54.120 --> 15:57.000
It's just, as you mentioned, how much it's going to cost

15:57.000 --> 15:59.800
and how much benefit are we going to get for each dollar spent?

16:00.120 --> 16:07.080
It's beyond obvious the money matters, or symmetrically follow the money,

16:07.080 --> 16:10.840
as the old ad is about saying who benefits from different policies.

16:10.840 --> 16:12.200
But here's the problem.

16:12.200 --> 16:15.400
It's not only is the rest of the world increasing its carbon dioxide emissions

16:15.400 --> 16:20.600
as the West tries to reduce it at extraordinarily high costs.

16:21.240 --> 16:22.840
It's that it's not doing what people claim.

16:23.480 --> 16:27.240
I mean, it's dishonest, intellectually dishonest,

16:27.240 --> 16:30.760
to pretend, for example, the electric cars are zero emissions.

16:30.760 --> 16:31.240
They're not.

16:31.240 --> 16:32.520
They're elsewhere emissions.

16:32.520 --> 16:36.680
What you'd want to know is how much the emissions are today

16:37.480 --> 16:42.760
and how much they will be in the future as you push harder on getting more EVs in the market

16:44.280 --> 16:48.440
to result in the higher emissions to make the vehicles.

16:49.160 --> 16:52.120
Obviously, it offsets emissions from combusting gasoline.

16:52.120 --> 16:55.480
This is beyond obvious and infantile observation,

16:55.480 --> 16:56.600
but it's not zero emissions.

16:57.160 --> 16:58.680
It's other place emissions.

16:59.720 --> 17:01.800
People know that reflexively when you say it.

17:01.800 --> 17:04.360
I mean, they say, OK, yeah, well, I have to have a power plant

17:04.360 --> 17:06.920
and everybody jokes about how the power plant could be coal fired.

17:06.920 --> 17:08.040
Well, that's no joke.

17:08.040 --> 17:09.160
I mean, it depends.

17:09.160 --> 17:10.680
It depends on where you charge the car.

17:11.320 --> 17:15.160
And when you charge the car, how you're filling that battery up.

17:15.160 --> 17:19.560
I mean, this may be obvious, but it's most of the calculations that purport

17:19.560 --> 17:23.640
an electric vehicle is zero emissions are based on average emissions from a grid.

17:24.360 --> 17:25.720
Well, there's no average.

17:25.720 --> 17:29.400
There's no average emissions in filling the vehicle.

17:29.400 --> 17:33.400
When the vehicle is fueled is when the emissions occur.

17:33.400 --> 17:37.320
So if you fuel the vehicle at night in some parts of the United States,

17:37.320 --> 17:40.120
you're filling it with hydro hydro electricity in other places.

17:40.120 --> 17:41.560
Let me just let me just drill down on this.

17:41.560 --> 17:45.800
And so we're on the same page and our listeners could get this.

17:46.760 --> 17:48.040
